\b - How much is Power BI?\par
\tab FREE\par
\b0\par
- Excel vs Power BI\par
\tab - Excel is a report-based tool. Simple to use but too many copy and paste techniques.\par
\tab - Power BI is a model-based tool that you can create reports on top of a data model. Once defined the model, you can build differenr reports with the same data.\par
\tab - During the development of our dashboard I will compare both tools again.\par
\par
\b\par
\b0 -----------------------------------------------------\par
\b 1) Extract\b0\par
\b\par
\b0 Where does data come from?\par
Generaly from an OLTP database. But the way we connect to this data can vary across organizations, mainly due to security reasons.\par
\par
How do you get the data you work with today?\par
\b\par
\b0\tab 1) Connecting directly in the transactional database (OLTP)\par
\tab 2) Connecting to a Data Warehouse (DW)\par
\tab 3) Through an Excel file connected to the database\par
\b\tab 4) Extracting reports from the ERP system\par
\tab 5) Filling out spreadsheets manually\b0\line\par
\b\par
\b0 -----------------------------------------------------\par
\b 2) Transform\b0\par
\b\line\b0 - What is the correct structure of a table?\par
\b\tab - Always columnar \par
\tab - Each column must represent a unique type of information\par
\par
\b0 - When you deal with real data, it is usually messy and dirty\par
\tab - So it is extremely important to TRANSFORM it before loading into the model\b\par
\par
- Power Query is our best friend for this. It is the tool to prepare, transform and put the data into the right shape\par
- Even better: you do this only once, because it automates all your ETL process\par
\par
\par
\b0 -----------------------------------------------------\par
\b 3) Modeling\b0\par
\b\par
\b0 - We always have to think about two types of table:\par
\par
\tab 1) Dimension tables: \par
\tab\tab - Describe business entities, the things in our model.\par
\tab\tab - Lookup tables, the What, When, Where, Who.\par
\tab\tab - They store the perspectives, the attributes of the entities, their descriptions.\par
\tab\tab - Must contain a key column that acts as a unique identifier.\par
\tab\tab - They are used to filter and group the values you want to analyze\par
\tab\tab - You use them usualy in the axis of the visuals and on slicers.\par
\tab\tab - Usually short but wide (not so many rows and lots of columns).\par
\tab\tab - Ex: products, customers, suppliers, accounts, etc\par
\par
\tab 2) Fact tables:\par
\tab\tab - Data table, the transactions, events that happen over time.\par
\tab\tab - Usually there is a date associated to an event.\par
\tab\tab - Contains dimension key columns that relate to dimension tables, and numeric columns.\par
\tab\tab - Can be very tall (and grow over time) but usualy thin (lots of rows and not so many columns).\par
\tab\tab - Ex: sales orders, stock balances, financial transactions, temperatures, etc.\par
\b\par
\par
\par
\b0 -----------------------------------------------------\par
\b 4) Calculation\b0\par
\b\par
\b0 - DAX: Data Analysis eXpressions\par
\par

\pard\nowidctlpar\sl276\slmult1\f1 - We can create columns, measures or tables with DAX\par
\tab 1) Columns: consume memory and are static calculations. Use it for descriptive information on the Axis and Filters.\par
\tab 2) Measures: are dynamic and consume only CPU, because they are calculated on the fly. Use always for Math (numbers that you place in the Values of the visuals);\par
\tab 3) Tables: not used often. It is better to create them in Power Query, with exception to the Date table.\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1\b\f0\par

