\b 5) Visuals\b0\par
\b\par
\b0 - What is Data Storytelling?\line\tab -> The power of building a narrative around a set of data to help convey the meaning of that data in a powerful and compelling fashion \line\tab\tab {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://tdwi.org/portals/what-is-data-storytelling-definition.aspx }}{\fldrslt{https://tdwi.org/portals/what-is-data-storytelling-definition.aspx\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22\par
\tab -> In other words, to guide your audience smoothly through the analysis.\par
\tab -> A dashboard is like a joke. If you have to explain that's because it was not good.\par
\b\par
\b0 - Recomendations:\par
\tab 1) Identify your audience\par
\tab\tab - Ask how a dashboard will be used and design for next step actions\par
\tab\tab - What information does the reader need to be successful?\par
\tab\tab - How much detail does the reader need?\par
\tab 2) Draw a sketch\par
\tab\tab - Good design should tell a story with data that does not become overwhelming with way too much information, clutter or noise. \par
\tab\tab - Limit content to fit entirely on one screen.\par
\tab\tab - Keep your dashboard simple with only a 3 to 5 key values, charts, or tables. Avoid putting too much information on a dashboard.\par
\tab\tab - If detail tables are needed, place them on the bottom of the dashboard\par
\tab 3) Choose the right visuals\par
\tab 4) Choose the right theme and keep consistency\par
\tab\tab - {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://color.adobe.com/explore }}{\fldrslt{https://color.adobe.com/explore\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22\par

\pard\li720\sl276\slmult1\b 5) Create a background (WOW effect)\par
\b0 6) Use icons and images to add context \par
\tab - {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://logomakr.com }}{\fldrslt{https://logomakr.com\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs22\par
